Exploring the Golf Digest and Golf Magazine Rankings

Every two years, Golf Digest and Golf Magazine issue widely read and debated rankings of the nations best golf courses. This has been a decades-long undertaking - Golf Digest has released rankings from #1 to #100 since 1985, while Golf Digest followed suit starting in 1991. (Golf Digest has actually been in this game even longer than that - before 1985 they grouped courses into First 10 through Fifth 10 and the Second 50, which makes more sense but doesnt sell as many magazines.)

Ranking golf courses, like ranking colleges, is both a fools errand and a natural instinct, a pointless exercise as well as a major feather in the cap for courses across the country. Golfers cant help but compare and contrast the courses they have played, and those comparisons can be quantified and sorted. Thanks to numerical rankings, however problematic they may be, over time can see changes in the way golf has been viewed and changes in how players value different course attributes and styles of architecture.

Until now, there hasnt been an easily searchable and viewable way to explore the history of these rankings. Golf Digest and Golf Magazine do not make their data easily available and their data visualizations are practically nil. Visualizations and infographics are critical in allowing us to track trends over time, make links and associations, and generate clusters of similar courses.

Typos and incorrect information are almost assured; indeed, there is sometimes conflicting or missing information even within the same publication. Please feel free to send over corrections, fixes and suggestions to golfcourserankings@gmail.com.

The blue bloods (click the title to view individual charts)

Course Location Year Designed Golf Digest Golf Magazine Average
Pine Valley Pine Valley, NJ 1918 1 1 1.0
Augusta National Augusta, GA 1933 2 3 2.5
Cypress Point Pebble Beach, CA 1928 3 2 2.5
Shinnecock Hills Southampton, NY 1931 4 4 4.0
Oakmont Oakmont, PA 1903 5 6 5.5
Merion Ardmore, PA 1912 6 8 7.0
Pebble Beach Pebble Beach, CA 1919 7 7 7.0

In both publications, the top 10 is rarefied air that has been occupied almost exclusively by a small number of classic courses built during golfs golden age of design. The position of these tracks has not just been lofty, but also remarkably durable:

  • Pine Valley (top 2 in every ranking in both publications)
  • Cypress Point (top 5 in every ranking)
  • Augusta National (top 5 in every ranking)
  • Shinnecock Hills (top 6 in every ranking)
  • Pebble Beach (top 7 in every ranking)
  • Oakmont (top 8 in every ranking since 1993)
  • Merion (top 8 in every ranking since 1995)

Golf Magazines ratings have been especially stable (ossified?) at the top - Pine Valley and Cypress Point have been ranked #1 and #2, respectively, in every edition since the first publication in 1991.

With the exception of Pebble Beach, membership rolls at these courses are populated by captains of industry and they are nearly impossible to get on for the average golfer. Interestingly, not all are tournament-ready - Pine Valley has never hosted professional events, Cypress Point pulled out of the Bing Crosby Clambake more than 30 years ago, and Merion only recently returned to the major championship rota - but the rest are current and former hosts of some of the most renowned and important competitions.

One noteworthy development in this largely static grouping is Golf Magazine putting Augusta National on notice with a column disparaging the clubs recent design changes. Is Augustas perennial top 5 streak about to end? More importantly, like the Old Course at St.Andrews, are technological changes making these blue bloods obsolete for PGA Tour pros? (The answer is yes)


The new (and newly revitalized) blue bloods

Course Location Year Designed Golf Digest Golf Magazine Average
National Golf Links Southampton, NY 1911 8 5 6.5
Sand Hills Mullen, NE 1995 9 9 9.0
Fishers Island Fishers Island, NY 1926 10 11 10.5
Friars Head Baiting Hollow, NY 2002 15 21 18.0

Like high society in real life, entry into the top echelons from the outside is rare but not impossible. Three courses have made a move into the top 10, two by staging sensational comebacks and the other by single-handedly changing the course of golf course architecture in the new millennium. National was once ranked #56 by Golf Digest and #26 by Golf Magazine but is now at #5 and #8, respectively, while Fishers Island, currently #10 and #11, was out of the top 100 altogether in Golf Digest as recently as 1999.

At #9 in both rankings, Sand Hills standing is perhaps the most remarkable on the entire list. The highly influential 1995 Coore/Crenshaw design is more than 60 years newer than the second-youngest top 10 course (Augusta National, 1933) and it is the only course located between Oakmont on the east and Monterey on the west. Friars Head, another Coore/Crenshaw collaboration, is a borderline case for the blue blood label but deserves kudos for breaking into the top 15 in Golf Digest.

These courses have been mainstays in the top 20 in one or the other of the two rankings, but have consistently been placed one notch below the blue bloods. As before, there is a rough 50/50 split between major championship venues and clubs that have shunned the attention and inconvenience that tournaments bring.
